{"ts": "2026-06-06T19:40:06.000Z", "event": "planner", "msg": "L3 task decomposition", "agent": "planner-l3", "tokens_in": 667, "tokens_out": 1266, "elapsed_ms": 21212, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Level 3 Planner. Decompose the user task into subtasks for dynamic agent creation.\n\nOutput JSON:\n{{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {{\"task_id\": \"short-name\", \"description\": \"What this worker must produce — ALWAYS include the user's exact request at the top\"}}\n  ]\n}}\n\n## Critical Rules\n- Each subtask description MUST begin with \"USER REQUEST: <exact user task text>\" — this prevents worker hallucination\n- Each subtask must be focused, self-contained, with explicit output file names\n- Never create duplicate task_ids — each worker name must be unique\n- For simple tasks, 3-4 subtasks; for complex tasks, 4-6\n- Always include a \"tester\" as the FINAL subtask — running test_report.json validation\n- Specify exact file names each worker must produce (e.g. \"Write to styles.css\", \"Write to app.js\")\n- Workers receive NO prior context beyond their subtask description — be thorough in the description\n- Output ONLY the JSON object — no markdown fences, no extra text\n\n## Specialty\nfrontend\n\n## User Request\nA modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\n\nFor frontend tasks, you MUST follow these constraints:\n- Always include a final \"integration\" subtask that merges all content/fragments into index.html\n- Always include a \"tester\" subtask as the VERY LAST subtask\n- Good decomposition: [content, html_structure, styling, interactivity, integration, tester]\n- Bad decomposition: [hero_builder, features_builder, cta_builder] — these create standalone pages\n- Each subtask description MUST include the user's verbatim request text at the top\n- Section subtasks produce content fragments into shared files, NOT standalone HTML files\n- The pipeline produces ONE web page: index.html + styles.css + app.js\n\n## CSS-HTML Coordination\n- The HTML worker MUST add semantic CSS classes to every major section (class=\"hero\", class=\"features\", class=\"cta\", class=\"footer\" etc.)\n- The styling worker's subtask MUST say: \"read_file('index.html') FIRST. Write CSS selectors matching the EXACT classes/IDs/elements found in index.html. Do NOT invent new class names.\"\n- The integration subtask MUST include: \"1) read index.html to see classes used, 2) read content.txt for real text, 3) read styles.css to see which classes need to exist, 4) write_file('index.html') with content injected AND missing CSS classes added, 5) read_file('index.html') to verify.\"\n\n## Token Efficiency\n- Each worker≈100K token budget limit for the entire pipeline, plan your decomposition and worker complexity accordingly\n- Avoid micro-workers that do trivial tasks — combine related work into fewer, more substantial workers\n- The CSS/styling worker should NOT call validate_css more than 3 times total", "meta": {}}
{"ts": "2026-06-06T19:40:57.000Z", "event": "agent_creator", "msg": "Agent Creator L3 — generating workers", "agent": "agent-creator-l3", "tokens_in": 2235, "tokens_out": 3211, "elapsed_ms": 51065, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Advanced Agent Creator (Level 3 — Fully Autonomous). Your role: create worker agents from scratch with custom system instructions, tools, and dynamic code tools.\n\n## Available Tools\nThe tool menu for this specialty:\n[\"read_file\", \"write_file\", \"list_files\", \"run_command\", \"render_html_screenshot\", \"render_html_file_screenshot\", \"validate_html\", \"validate_css\", \"read_image\", \"generate_image\"]\n\n## Task Plan\nThe planner has decomposed the task into subtasks:\n{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"content\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: A modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\\n\\nGather and write all textual content and image descriptions needed for the landing page. Write to content.txt with the following sections clearly labeled: HERO_HEADLINE, HERO_SUBHEADLINE, FEATURES (with 4 feature titles and descriptions), CUSTOMER_LOGOS (list 6 fictional but realistic tech companies), PRICING_PLANS (3 tiers: Basic, Pro, Enterprise with price and features), TESTIMONIALS (3 quotes with names and roles), CTA_HEADLINE, CTA_BUTTON. Include description of dashboard mockup image for use in hero section.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"html_structure\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: A modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\\n\\nCreate a minimal HTML skeleton in index.html with doctype, lang=en, charset, viewport, and title 'FlowSync - AI Project Management for Remote Teams'. Add semantic sections with the following classes: class='hero', class='features', class='logos', class='pricing', class='testimonials', class='cta', class='footer'. Use placeholder text only. Ensure all sections are in correct order and use semantic HTML5 tags (header, section, article, footer). Do NOT include inline styles or scripts.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"styling\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: A modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\\n\\nread_file('index.html') FIRST. Write CSS selectors matching the EXACT classes/IDs/elements found in index.html. Do NOT invent new class names. Write to styles.css with a clean, modern design using a purple and white color scheme (primary: #8A3FFC, secondary: #F8F9FC). Use a modern sans-serif font stack (e.g., Inter, -apple-system, sans-serif). Style all sections: hero (full-width, centered text, mockup image placeholder), features (grid layout), logos (horizontal flex with grayscale logos), pricing (3-column flex or grid), testimonials (carousel style, quotes in cards), cta (bold headline and button). Ensure mobile responsiveness with media queries. Button styles should match Notion/Linear aesthetic (subtle shadow, rounded corners, hover effect).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"interactivity\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: A modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\\n\\nWrite JavaScript for basic UI interactions. Write to app.js. Implement: 1) testimonial carousel with next/prev buttons, 2) mobile menu toggle for responsive navigation (add nav.menu-toggle and .nav-menu if not present), 3) smooth scroll for all anchor links, 4) form validation for trial signup (simulate success with alert). Assume HTML includes necessary data attributes or classes for targeting. Do NOT modify HTML structure.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"integration\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: A modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\\n\\n1) read index.html to see classes used, 2) read content.txt for real text, 3) read styles.css to see which classes need to exist, 4) write_file('index.html') with content injected AND missing CSS classes added, 5) read_file('index.html') to verify. Inject real content from content.txt into correct sections of index.html. Add <script src='app.js'> and <link rel='stylesheet' href='styles.css'> in head/body. Insert image placeholder in hero: <img src='mockup-dashboard.png' alt='FlowSync Dashboard'>. Ensure all interactive elements have correct IDs/classes for JS. Final output must be a single, valid index.html with full content and structure.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"tester\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: A modern landing page for a startup called FlowSync, an AI-powered project management platform for remote teams. Include a hero section with a product dashboard mockup, key features section, customer logos, pricing plans, testimonials, and a call-to-action to start a free trial. Use a clean purple and white design inspired by Linear and Notion.\\n\\nRun validate_html('index.html'), validate_css('styles.css'), and validate_js('app.js'). Generate test_report.json with pass/fail for each test. Verify: HTML5 compliance, CSS syntax, JS syntax, mobile viewport, image alt text, form accessibility, and responsive layout. If any test fails, include error details and file locations. Output only the JSON test report.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\n## Specialty-Specific Architecture Constraints\nFor FRONTEND specialty:\n- One worker MUST produce index.html as the canonical entry page\n- All CSS lives in ONE shared styles.css file. All JavaScript in ONE shared app.js file.\n- Workers write SECTIONS INTO these shared files — they do NOT create standalone HTML pages.\n- If you create section-specific workers (hero, features, cta),\n  the pipeline MUST end with an integrator that merges all sections\n  into a single index.html with linked styles.css and app.js.\n- Never design a pipeline where each worker produces its own standalone HTML page.\n- The user expects ONE complete web page, not a collection of separate HTML files.\n\n## HTML-CSS Coordination (CRITICAL — prevents broken pages)\nEvery CSS worker system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'iCRITICAL: read_file(\"index.html\") FIRST before writing any CSS. Your selectors MUST match actual elements/classes/IDs in the HTML.'\n- 'Use the SAME class naming convention as the HTML. If HTML uses class=\"hero\", write .hero {{}}. Never invent new class names.'\nEvery HTML worker system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'Add semantic CSS classes to ALL major sections: class=\"header\", class=\"hero\", class=\"features\", class=\"cta\", class=\"footer\" etc.'\n- 'Use class selectors (not just bare element tags) so the CSS worker can target them reliably.'\nEvery integrator system_prompt MUST include:\n- '1. read_file(\"index.html\") to see current HTML structure and classes'\n- '2. Inject real content from content.txt INTO the existing HTML — do NOT rewrite the HTML from scratch'\n- '3. Add any missing CSS classes to elements that the stylesheet targets'\n- '4. write_file(\"index.html\", ...) to save — NEVER skip this step'\n- '5. read_file(\"index.html\") to verify the merge succeeded'\n\n## Conversation History & Memory Protocol (MUST include in every worker prompt)\nEvery worker's system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'Your conversation history is LIMITED. The LLM only sees the last 3 tool-call turns.'\n- 'Use WORKSPACE FILES as your persistent memory — always read_file() at start of iteration.'\n- 'Do NOT re-read unchanged files — use list_files to verify existence instead.'\n- 'Tool results from read_file are truncated to 3000 chars and cached.'\n- 'After completing, write exactly ONE final output file and STOP. Do not iterate needlessly.'\n\n\n## Your Job\nFor EACH subtask in the plan:\n1. WRITE a custom system_prompt from scratch — give the worker clear role, boundaries, and workflow\n2. SELECT tools from the available tool menu that the worker needs\n3. If available tools are insufficient, CREATE dynamic_tools as Python code strings\n4. Optionally create inline_skills as text fragments (not loaded from files)\n\n## Dynamic Tools (Python code strings)\nDynamic tools are Python functions the worker can call. Write them as complete, executable code strings.\nExample:\n  \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \"fetch_api\", \"code\": \"import httpx\\nasync def fetch_api(url):\\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as c:\\n        return (await c.get(url)).text\", \"description\": \"Fetch data from an API\"}]\n\n## Rules\n- Output ONLY valid JSON — no markdown fences, no extra text\n- worker_name: give each worker a unique short name (e.g. \"scraper\", \"analyzer\", \"validator\")\n- system_prompt: must be detailed — role, boundaries, tools to use, workflow, output format\n- tool_names: only from the available tool menu\n- dynamic_tools: list of {name, code, description} — only create if needed\n- inline_skills: list of prompt fragments for worker knowledge\n\n## Output Format\n{\n  \"workers\": [\n    {\n      \"worker_name\": \"unique_name\",\n      \"system_prompt\": \"Full custom system instructions\",\n      \"tool_names\": [\"tool1\", \"tool2\"],\n      \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \".\", \"code\": \".\", \"description\": \".\"}],\n      \"inline_skills\": [\"Skill fragment text...\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "meta": {}}
